<p>*1412404* 
</p>
<p><b>Human Rights Council 
Twenty-fifth session 
</b>Agenda item 1 
<b>Organizational and procedural matters 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Ethiopia (on behalf of the Group of African States), South Sudan:* statement by the 
President 
</b></p>
<p><b>  PRST 25/&#8230;  Situation of human rights in South Sudan 
</b></p>
<p>At the &#8230; meeting, held on &#8230; March 2014, the President of the Human Rights 
Council read out the following statement: 
</p>
<p>&#8220;The Human Rights Council: 
</p>
<p>(a) Expresses deep concern at the situation of human rights resulting from 
the crisis and violence that broke out in mid-December 2013 in South Sudan; 
</p>
<p>(b) Acknowledges the relevant communiqu&#233;s and resolutions issued by 
the Intergovernmental Authority on Development, the African Union and the 
United Nations, and the statements made by United Nations High 
Commissioner for Human Rights, in which they urged the parties to the 
conflict to protect the civilian population from violence and to ensure full 
respect for human rights and fundamental freedoms; 
</p>
<p>(c) Calls upon the parties to the conflict to put an end to all violations and 
abuses of human rights and international humanitarian law, including attacks 
against and killings of civilians and the mass displacement of populations, 
and to implement the Cessation of Hostilities Agreement and its 
Implementation Modalities, as well as to show their political will and 
commitment to end the conflict through dialogue, reconciliation and 
peacebuilding; 
</p>
<p>(d) Expresses support for the democratically elected Government of South 
Sudan, encourages the Government to investigate the root causes of the crisis 
and the violence that broke out in mid-December 2013, and reiterates that all 
perpetrators of atrocities must be held accountable; 
</p>
<p>(e) Commends the leading role played by the Intergovernmental 
Authority on Development in mediating between the parties to the conflict to 
</p>
<p>  
</p>
<p> * Non-member State of the Human Rights Council. 
</p>
<p> 
</p>

<p>sign the Cessation of Hostilities Agreement, and the formation of a 
monitoring and verification team; 
</p>
<p>(f) Calls upon the international community, United Nations mechanisms 
and the Office of the High Commissioner to support the efforts of the African 
Union and the Intergovernmental Authority on Development; 
</p>
<p>(g) Urges the parties to the conflict to allow immediate and full access to 
humanitarian assistance to all populations in need of assistance, in 
accordance with humanitarian principles, to facilitate the efforts of 
humanitarian agencies to address the critical humanitarian crisis, and to 
explore durable solutions for refugees and internally displaced persons, in 
collaboration and coordination with local and international humanitarian 
organizations; 
</p>
<p>(h) Welcomes the establishment by the African Union of a commission of 
inquiry for South Sudan as an important step towards ensuring accountability 
and preventing the recurrence of such abuses; 
</p>
<p>(i) Calls upon the Government of South Sudan to cooperate fully with the 
United Nations Mission in South Sudan in accordance with the Status of 
Forces Agreement signed in August 2011; 
</p>
<p>(j) Encourages the Government of South Sudan to continue to engage 
with the Intergovernmental Authority on Development, the Human Rights 
Council and the Office of the High Commissioner on this matter.&#8221; 
</p>
<p>    </p>

